1530":"about 1530","Abt 1505":"about 1505","1505":"1505","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Tripp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>trip(pe) (n)</i> ‘(to) dance; stumble’ (Old French <i>tripe(r)</i>), either an occupational name for a dancer, or a nickname for someone who had difficulty walking.","English: metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>trip(e)</i> ‘tripe’ (Old French <i>tripe</i>).","German: metonymic occupational name for a maker of wooden pattens (<i>trippe</i>), a type of raised sole that could be strapped to normal footwear for walking in unpaved muddy streets."],"variants":[{"name":"Trepp","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Tripp  ."]},{"name":"Trippe","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Somerset) or German: variant of   Tripp  . This form of the English name is very rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Rose Tripp was born about 1505, in Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She married Robert Tripp in Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She was buried in Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1505–":"umbes 1505–Surnud","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1525–1568":"1525–1568","1530–1568":"1530–1568","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1525":"1525","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","about 1530":"umbes 1530","Abt 1505":"umbes 1505","1505":"1505","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1505–":"noin 1505–Kuollut","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1525–1568":"1525–1568","1530–1568":"1530–1568","1505–Female":"1505–Kuollut","1525":"1525","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","about 1530":"noin 1530","Abt 1505":"noin 1505","1505":"1505","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1505–":"environ 1505–Décédée","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1525–1568":"1525–1568","1530–1568":"1530–1568","1505–Female":"1505–Décédée","1525":"1525","1568":"1568","1500":"1500","1530":"1530","1550":"1550","about 1530":"environ 1530","Abt 1505":"environ 1505","1505":"1505","Lavenham, Suffolk, England":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Lavenham, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Lavenham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Rose Tripp est née environ 1505, à Lavenham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a épousé Robert Tripp à Lavenham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 2 fils. Elleenterrée à Lavenham, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"Abt 1505–":"um 1505–Verstorben","1500–1550":"1500–1550","1525–1